<p>
<seg id="1">Stores in Australia have lowered the ceiling on the number of toilet paper per transaction</seg>
<seg id="2">On Sunday and Saturday evenings, Australian chains Woolworths and Coles reduced the ceiling on the purchase of toilet paper per transaction in all their stores to two and one packs, respectively, nationwide.</seg>
<seg id="3">ALDI also introduced a one-pack restriction on Monday.</seg>
<seg id="4">These restrictions are posted on the cashier's desk or posted on the chain's Facebook page in the form of messages.</seg>
<seg id="5">Buyers hoarded goods for fear of COVID-19 in case they needed to isolate themselves, the report said.</seg>
<seg id="6">On Wednesday, Woolworths also limited the number of door-to-door toilet paper purchases to a single pack.</seg>
<seg id="7">Prior to these changes, Woolworths and Coles introduced a limit of four packs per transaction on March 4 and 5, respectively.</seg>
<seg id="8">In its March 8 press release, Coles reported that after the implementation of the four-pack restriction, "many stores still sold out within an hour of arrival" and called the demand "unprecedented", while ALDI called it "unexpected" in a Facebook post on Tuesday.</seg>
<seg id="9">According to a Woolworths spokesman, sales rose "sharply" last week.</seg>
<seg id="10">Last week, the Costco store in Canberra also limited the number allowed to two packs.</seg>
<seg id="11">To further alleviate the shortage, Coles ordered larger packaging from suppliers and increased the frequency of delivery, Woolworths ordered additional stock, while ALDI prepared stock in advance for the planned Wednesday special.</seg>
<seg id="12">Russell Zimmerman, executive director of the Australian Retailers Association, said retailers were trying to increase inventories, but local council restrictions on truck delivery times made this difficult.</seg>
<seg id="13">He expects that as suppliers try to meet demand, production costs will rise and preferential activities will decrease.</seg>
<seg id="14">On Tuesday, ALDI announced that some stores would not be able to hold Wednesday's special event after the early release of stockpiles.</seg>
<seg id="15">In a report by News.Com. Au, Dr. Gary Mortimer, a retail expert at Queensland University of Technology, said stores replenish their stock every night.</seg>
<seg id="16">He said that toilet paper is a large item, so the inventory is small. Moreover, once sold out, it will leave a huge shelf space, exacerbating the feeling of material shortage.</seg>
<seg id="17">"The view of Coles and Woolworths is that if there are a lot of things on the shelves, such as rolls of paper and hand sanitizers, that can be [bought] and in sufficient quantities, you may not be so panicked," Russell Zimmerman told ABC News.</seg>
<seg id="18">Who Gives a Crap, a maker of recycled toilet paper, said last Wednesday that it was out of stock.</seg>
<seg id="19">According to News.Com. Au, Kimberly-Clark, who makes Shujie toilet paper, and Solaris Paper, who makes Sorbent toilet paper, both emphasize that they are working around the clock and on weekends to ensure supply.</seg>
<seg id="20">Real estate website Domain.com reported that some real estate agents will offer free toilet paper to the first bidder at an auction in Melbourne because buyers take a long weekend off on Labor Day and hold fewer auctions.</seg>
<seg id="21">NT News, a daily newspaper printed in Darwin, includes an eight-page insert in its Thursday edition, designed to be cut and used as toilet paper.</seg>
<seg id="22">According to a report by ABC Australia on March 3, stores were initially reluctant to impose purchase restrictions. They said they did not plan to impose purchase restrictions.</seg>
<seg id="23">Russell Zimmerman added that there was also a high demand for other goods, including masks, hand sanitizers, dry goods, hand sanitizers and flour.</seg>
<seg id="24">Similarly, outside Australia, Ocado, the UK online supermarket, limited the purchase of Andres toilet paper to two packs of 12 rolls each on Sunday night.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
