<seg id="1">COVID-19 workplace prevention and control</seg>
<seg id="2">COVID-19 workplace prevention and control refers to the use of occupational safety and health measures to prevent coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19).</seg>
<seg id="3">The appropriateness of workplace hazard prevention and control depends on the specific work site and work task, and should be determined on the basis of the risk assessment of the source of exposure, the severity of the disease in the community and the risk factors of vulnerable individuals who may be exposed to COVID-19.</seg>
<seg id="4">According to the requirements of the United States Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), low-exposure work has the least occupational contact with the public and other colleagues, so it is recommended to take basic infection prevention measures, including washing hands frequently, encouraging employees to be isolated at home after illness, observing respiratory etiquette and daily cleaning and disinfection of the working environment.</seg>
<seg id="5">Medium-exposure work includes work that requires regular or close contact with unknown or suspected COVID-19 patients, who may be infected as a result of continuous community transmission or international travel.</seg>
<seg id="6">This includes staff who come into contact with the general public, such as schools, high-density work environments and some large-scale retail environments.</seg>
<seg id="7">In addition to basic infection prevention measures, the group should also use high-efficiency air filters and sneezing protective devices for ventilation, wear personal protective equipment and take other risk prevention and control measures when in contact with COVID-19 patients.</seg>
<seg id="8">OSHA believes that there is a high risk of exposure to medical personnel and mortuary staff who come into contact with known or suspected COVID-19 patients. If staff perform aerosol-producing operations on known or suspected COVID-19 patients or collect or process specimens from them, the risk of exposure becomes extremely high.</seg>
<seg id="9">Hazard prevention and control measures applicable to such personnel include engineering controls, such as negative pressure ventilation rooms and personal protective equipment suitable for their work tasks.</seg>
<seg id="10">The outbreak of COVID-19 could have a serious impact on the workplace.</seg>
<seg id="11">Staff may be absent from work due to illness, need to take care of others or fear of exposure.</seg>
<seg id="12">Business models may also change, including changes in demand for goods or changes in access to these goods (such as shopping during off-peak hours or using distribution or drop-off delivery services).</seg>
<seg id="13">Finally, product logistics from areas with severe COVID-19 epidemics may be disrupted. Infectious disease prevention and response plans can be used to guide protection actions.</seg>
<seg id="14">These plans address the level of risk associated with various workplaces and work tasks, including sources of exposure, risk factors from the family and community environment and risk factors for individual workers, such as the elderly or groups with chronic diseases.</seg>
<seg id="15">These plans also outline the prevention and control measures needed to address these risks, as well as contingency plans for situations that may arise as a result of the outbreak.</seg>
<seg id="16">Infectious disease prevention and response plans may need to be subject to national or local recommendations.</seg>
<seg id="17">The goals of responding to the outbreak include reducing inter-employee transmission, protecting people at high risk of adverse health complications, maintaining business operations, and minimizing adverse effects on other entities in the supply chain.</seg>
<seg id="18">In addition, the response will also be affected by the severity of the disease in the community in which the enterprise is located.</seg>
<seg id="19">The hazard prevention and control level is a widely used prevention and control framework in occupational safety and health. It is used to group hazard prevention and control measures according to their effectiveness.</seg>
<seg id="20">If the hazards of COVID-19 cannot be completely eliminated, the most effective control measures are engineering control, followed by administrative control, and finally personal protective equipment.</seg>
<seg id="21">Engineering control refers to isolating employees from work-related hazards rather than relying on employees' behavior for control, which is also the least costly solution to implement.</seg>
<seg id="22">Administrative control refers to changing work policies or procedures and requiring staff or employers to take action on their own.</seg>
<seg id="23">The prevention and control effect of personal protective equipment (PPE) is lower than that of engineering control and administrative control, but it helps to prevent some exposure.</seg>
<seg id="24">All types of PPE should be selected according to the level of risk faced by the staff, equipped according to the applicable circumstances (such as respirators), and must always be worn correctly, regularly inspected and maintained, replaced if necessary, and properly removed, cleaned, stored or disposed of to avoid pollution.</seg>
<seg id="25">According to the United States Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), low-exposure work has the least occupational contact with the public and other colleagues.</seg>
<seg id="26">It is recommended that all workplaces should take basic infection prevention measures, including washing hands frequently, advising sick employees to be isolated at home, abide by breathing etiquette when coughing or sneezing, provide paper towels and garbage cans, be prepared to work remotely, commute to and from work at the wrong peak if necessary, dissuade employees from using the tools and equipment of others, and keep the workplace clean and disinfected on a daily basis.</seg>
<seg id="27">Identifying and isolating potentially infectious individuals in a timely manner is the key to protecting workplace personnel, customers, visitors and others.</seg>
<seg id="28">The United States Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) recommends that employees who show acute respiratory symptoms should be isolated at home for at least 24 hours until it is determined that there are no fever, fever signs and any other symptoms, that the sick leave policy should be implemented flexibly, that employees should be allowed to take care of sick family members at home, and that employees should be clearly informed of the policy.</seg>
<seg id="29">According to OSHA, moderate exposure risk work includes work that requires frequent or close contact with unknown or suspected COVID-19 patients within a range of 6 feet (1.8 m), but may cause an individual to contract SARS-CoV-2 as a result of continuous community transmission near the workplace or as a result of a possible recent visit to the COVID-19 epidemic area.</seg>
<seg id="30">Such staff include staff working in schools, high population density working environments and some mass retail environments who will come into contact with the general public. Engineering control measures for this group and high-risk groups include the installation of efficient air filters, improve ventilation, install physical barriers such as transparent plastic sneezing protection devices and install drop-free windows to provide customer service. Administrative controls for this group and high-risk groups include encouraging sick employees to be isolated at home, replace face-to-face meetings with virtual communications, establish a staggered shift system, cancel non-essential travel to the COVID-19 outbreak site, formulate an emergency communication plan, including a forum to answer staff questions, and provide staff with the latest education and training on COVID-19 risk factors and protective behavior, provide training to staff who need to use protective clothing and protective equipment in the use of protective clothing and protective equipment, provide resources and working environment conducive to improving personal hygiene, require frequent hand washing, restrict customers and the public from entering the work site, and post signs on hand washing and other COVID-19 protective measures. According to specific work tasks, at a minimum, staff at risk of moderate exposure should be equipped with personal protective equipment, including gloves, robes, masks or goggles.</seg>
<seg id="31">It is advisable for such staff to be equipped with respirators.</seg>
<seg id="32">If someone falls ill on the plane, appropriate protective measures should be taken to protect staff and other passengers, including arranging the patient to a distance of 6 feet from other passengers, designating a crew member to serve the patient, providing the patient with a mask, or requiring the patient to cover his or her mouth and nose with a tissue when coughing or sneezing.</seg>
<seg id="33">Crew members should wear disposable medical gloves when caring for sick travelers, touching body fluids or potentially contaminated surfaces. If sick travelers have symptoms such as fever, persistent cough or difficulty breathing, crew members should also wear additional personal protective equipment.</seg>
<seg id="34">Gloves and other disposable items should be disposed of in a biohazard bag and the contaminated surface should then be cleaned and disinfected. For commercial transport, including cruise ships and other passenger ships, risk prevention and control measures also include postponing travel in the event of illness. If there is fever or other symptoms on board the ship, self-isolation should be carried out and the medical room on board should be notified immediately.</seg>
<seg id="35">Ideally, medical follow-up should be carried out in the compartment of the segregated person. For schools and childcare places, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommends that if the infected person has been present in the school, the corresponding schools and childcare places should be closed for a short period of time for thorough cleaning or disinfection, regardless of the spread of the community.</seg>
<seg id="36">For medium-and low-level community transmission, social distance strategies can be implemented, such as canceling other large gatherings such as field visits, rallies and physical education classes, chorus classes or cafeteria meals, increasing the distance between desks, arriving and leaving at the wrong peaks, limiting the visits of non-essential visitors, and arranging separate health offices for children with flu-like symptoms.</seg>
<seg id="37">If community transmission is serious, in addition to implementing a social distance strategy, consideration may also be given to extending the suspension time. For law enforcement personnel carrying out daily routine activities, the CDC considers that they face a lower direct health risk.</seg>
<seg id="38">It is recommended that law enforcement personnel who must come into contact with COVID-19 confirmed patients or suspected individuals should act in accordance with the same level of protection as emergency medical technicians, including appropriate personal protective equipment.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the event of close contact during the arrest, staff members should first clean and disinfect their service belts and equipment before cleaning them with household cleaning spray or rags, and should comply with standard personal protective equipment sealing and disposal procedures and clothing sealing and cleaning procedures.</seg>
<seg id="40">OSHA believes that some health care and mortuary workers face a high or very high risk of exposure.</seg>
<seg id="41">Staff at high risk of exposure include health care, support, laboratory and medical transport staff who actually come into contact with people known or suspected to be infected with COVID-19.</seg>
<seg id="42">If staff perform droplet generation procedures on known or suspected COVID-19 patients, or collect or process specimens of infected or suspected infected persons, the risk of exposure becomes extremely high.</seg>
<seg id="43">Droplet generation procedures include intubation, cough induction procedures, bronchoscopy, some dental procedures and examinations, or body cavity specimen collection.</seg>
<seg id="44">The staff of the high-exposure morgue includes staff involved in the collation of the bodies of the deceased, who were diagnosed or suspected cases of COVID-19 during their lifetime. If an autopsy is performed, they face a higher risk of exposure. Additional engineering measures to be taken for this risk group also include isolation rooms prepared for the diagnosis or suspected cases of COVID-19, including when performing droplet generation procedures.</seg>
<seg id="45">Some health care facilities and morgues can also be equipped with special negative pressure ventilation systems.</seg>
<seg id="46">Biosafety level 3 precautions should be taken when handling specimens.</seg>
<seg id="47">The World Health Organization (WTO) recommends that different waiting areas be designated for patients according to whether the patient is a suspected case of COVID-19. In addition to other personal protective equipment, the Occupational Safety and Health Administration also recommends that personnel working within 6 feet of patients known or suspected to have been infected with SARS-CoV-2, as well as those performing droplet generation procedures, wear respirators.</seg>
<seg id="48">The United States requires that N95 filter masks or better masks approved by the NIOSH must be used in a comprehensive written respiratory protection program environment such as health testing, training and medical examination.</seg>
<seg id="49">Other types of respirators can provide better protection and improve the comfort of staff. The WHO does not recommend the use of protective clothing because COVID-19 is a respiratory disease that is not transmitted through body fluids.</seg>
<seg id="50">The WHO recommends that screening personnel at entry points simply wear a medical surgical mask.</seg>
