<doc docid="testsuite-covid-PubMed_6" genre="news" origlang="zh" sysid="DeepMind">
<p>
<seg id="1">Between January 1 and March 15, 2020, the cumulative incidence of new coronavirus diseases (COVID-19) in the European Union/European Economic Area and the United Kingdom increased rapidly</seg>
<seg id="2">In various countries of the European Union/European Economic Area and the United Kingdom, the cumulative incidence of new coronavirus diseases (COVID-19) shows a similar trend, confirming that although different countries are at different stages, the COVID-19 pandemic is developing rapidly.</seg>
<seg id="3">According to the experience of Italy, the state, hospitals and intensive care wards need to be better prepared to meet the surge in the number of COVID-19 patients. The task of intensive care is particularly heavy.</seg>
<seg id="4">On December 31, 2019, Wuhan, Hubei Province, China, reported a number of cases of pneumonia with unknown cause.</seg>
<seg id="5">On January 9, 2020, the China Center for Disease Prevention and Control reported that the pathogen is a new type of coronavirus, now known as Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2).</seg>
<seg id="6">Since then, the disease caused by SARS-CoV-2 infection has been named coronavirus disease (COVID-19).</seg>
<seg id="7">Evidence to date shows that about 80% of COVID-19 cases are mild, i.e. respiratory infections with or without pneumonia, and most recover.</seg>
<seg id="8">In about 14% of cases, COVID-19 will progress to severe disease and require hospitalization, while the remaining 6% will progress to critical disease and require intensive care.</seg>
<seg id="9">The mortality rate of patients hospitalized for COVID-19 is about 4%.</seg>
<seg id="10">In this study, we assessed the trend of the cumulative incidence of COVID-19 in various countries of the European Union (EU)/European Economic Area (EEA) and the United Kingdom (UK), and compared it with Hubei Province of China.</seg>
<seg id="11">We also compared the number of existing COVID-19 cases in EU/EEA countries and the United Kingdom with Italy between January 31 and March 15, 2020.</seg>
<seg id="12">Cases of COVID-19 in EU/EEA countries and the United Kingdom</seg>
<seg id="13">After China, the geographical distribution of COVID-19 has further expanded. At present, the dynamics of the COVID-19 pandemic in other parts of the world are similar to those in China.</seg>
<seg id="14">On March 11, 2020, the Director-General of the World Health Organization (WHO) declared COVID-19 a pandemic.</seg>
<seg id="15">In the European Monitor magazine published on March 5, 2020, Spiteri et al. Reported the first confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Europe according to the WHO case definition.</seg>
<seg id="16">In EU/EEA, France reported the first three confirmed cases on January 24, 2020. The patient was a returnee from Wuhan, Hubei Province, China.</seg>
<seg id="17">As of March 15, 2020, COVID-19 cases had been detected in all 30 EU/EEA countries and the United Kingdom. From December 31 to March 15, 2019, including that date, 39,768 cases and 1,727 deaths had been reported, of which 17,750 cases and 1,441 deaths had been reported in Italy alone.</seg>
<seg id="18">Cumulative number and cumulative incidence of COVID-19 cases obtained</seg>
<seg id="19">The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) updates the number of COVID-19 cases reported by each country in the world at 8:00 am every day. They are obtained only through official sources, such as ministries of health, national and regional health authorities and WHO.</seg>
<seg id="20">These data have been used to assess trends in EU/EEA and COVID-19 in the United Kingdom and to compare them with Italy.</seg>
<seg id="21">We calculated the 14-day cumulative incidence of COVID-19 cases in each EU/EEA country and the United Kingdom between January 1 and March 15, 2020, as an indicator of the prevalence of active COVID-19 cases, in order to take into account the natural course of COVID-19.</seg>
<seg id="22">We also provided the total number of cumulative cases reported by each country as of 8:00 am on March 15, 2020, and compared it with the data of Italy for the period from January 31 to March 15, 2020.</seg>
<seg id="23">Trends in COVID-19 in EU/EEA countries and the United Kingdom</seg>
<seg id="24">The trend of 14-day cumulative incidence of COVID-19 cases in EU/EEA countries and the United Kingdom is generally consistent with that in Hubei Province (China) (Figure 1).</seg>
<seg id="25">For the EU/EEA and the UK as a whole, the cumulative incidence of COVID-19 began to increase around February 21, 2020, and then increased sharply around February 28 (supplementary material).</seg>
<seg id="26">This is mainly due to the rapid increase in the number of cases reported in Italy, but the cumulative incidence of COVID-19 in all other EU/EEA countries and the United Kingdom shows a similar growth trend (supplementary material).</seg>
<seg id="27">Figure 2 shows the cumulative number of COVID-19 cases in EU/EEA countries and the United Kingdom between January 31 and March 15, 2020, and compares them with Italy.</seg>
<seg id="28">It should be emphasized that as of 8:00 am on March 15, the other 15 EU/EEA countries and the UK had reported the same total number of cases as Italy in less than three weeks.</seg>
<seg id="29">Our results show that the number of COVID-19 cases reported by the EU/EEA and the UK is increasing rapidly.</seg>
<seg id="30">The observed trend of the cumulative incidence of COVID-19 shows that the epidemic is developing at a similar rate in all countries.</seg>
<seg id="31">Although countries are at different stages, national public health responses vary, the definition of cases may vary from country to country, and there are differences in the options used to select patients who must undergo COVID-19 diagnostic tests, including additional tests, but the situation is the same.</seg>
<seg id="32">In early March 2020, according to doctors in the affected areas of Italy, about 10% of COVID-19 patients need intensive care, and media reports indicate that hospitals and intensive care wards in these areas have reached their maximum capacity.</seg>
<seg id="33">At the EU/EEA level, the data currently available is that only 6% and 1% of COVID-19 cases are hospitalized/or admitted to intensive care wards, respectively (the data are not shown).</seg>
<seg id="34">However, this information should be collected in a systematic manner in order to supplement current monitoring data focusing on the number of reported cases and deaths.</seg>
<seg id="35">A study conducted in 2010-11 showed that there are great differences in the number of intensive care and medium-term care beds available in European countries. The number of beds per 100,000 people ranges from 29.2 in Germany to 4.2 in Portugal.</seg>
<seg id="36">This means that countries may have more or less resources than Italy (12.5 intensive care and medium-term care beds per 100,000 people in 2010-2011).</seg>
<seg id="37">The sixth update of the ECDC's rapid risk assessment of COVID-19 modeled the scenario related to the saturation of health care capacity and estimated the relationship between the prevalence of hospitalized COVID-19 patients in each EU/EEA country and the United Kingdom and the risk of exceeding the number of intensive care beds by &gt;90%.</seg>
<seg id="38">Since cases have so far been concentrated in EU/EEA countries and certain regions of the UK, and hospitals and intensive care wards usually provide services to the population covered in the identified areas, it is advisable to provide information on cases and intensive care beds at the level of "Standard Statistical Geographical Module 2" (NUTS-2).</seg>
<seg id="39">The experience of Italy and the current trends in other countries show that the EU/EEA and the COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom are developing rapidly.</seg>
<seg id="40">Therefore, the state, hospitals and intensive care wards should be prepared to deal with the continuous community transmission of SARS-CoV-2 and the increase in the number of COVID-19 patients in need of medical care, especially intensive care, such as in the affected areas of Italy.</seg>
<seg id="41">As the recent ECDC rapid risk assessment pointed out, a rapid, active and comprehensive approach is essential to delay the spread of SARS-COV-2. There needs to be a transition from containment to mitigation, because if not implemented ahead of schedule, the rapid increase in the number of expected cases may leave policymakers and hospitals with insufficient time to understand, accept and adjust the response.</seg>
<seg id="42">The rapid risk assessment also lists public health measures to mitigate the impact of the pandemic.</seg>
<seg id="43">At present, there is a short window of opportunity through which countries may further strengthen their control efforts in order to slow the spread of SARS-CoV-2 and reduce the pressure on the health care system.</seg>
<seg id="44">Otherwise, the health-care systems of other EU/EEA countries are likely to face a surge in the number of patients in need of intensive care in the coming days or weeks.</seg>
</p>
